<TITLE> Russia approves banks' transfer of N Korea funds </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 MOSCOW, June 13 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Russia is taking steps to ease the repatriation of North Korean funds from a Macau bank, action needed before Pyongyang will go ahead with a nuclear disarmament deal, Itar-Tass news agency quoted a government source as saying on Wednesday. "The appropriate operation is being prepared," a Russian finance ministry source told Tass. "There are several technical problems to solve related to ensuring Russia's legal interests. There are also issues related to a Russian bank's role in international fund transfer," the source said. Earlier in the day, the Russian foreign ministry gave the green light to its banks' participation in the transfer and indicated that the process was under way. "The Russian side ... does not mind a possible participation of the Russian banks in arranging a transfer of North Korean funds held on accounts in Delta Asia bank to North Korea," ministry spokesman Mikhail Kamynin said in a statement. "As of now, examination of all legal aspects related to their participation in this financial operation is under way which is aimed at preventing Russian banks from falling under U.S. sanctions among other things," it added. Pyongyang has refused to honour a February deal to begin shutting its Yangbyon nuclear reactor, the source of material for atomic bombs, until $25 million of its funds frozen in the Macau bank is released through normal banking channels. That would in effect allow the communist state back into the international banking system from which it is currently exclud
